I'm not a big fan of background checks and we don't do it unless it's
required by a customer contract for certain folks (none as of yet).

I'm not certain a work-specific laptop really does the trick, but if you
want to set up a virtual workstation using AWS's product or something
similar, that is certainly a better way to go. We DO generally buy our
contractor's equipment but I would say it's more about them operating on
the same OS/tools we are and less regarding security.

My general rule of thumb is that while policies and procedures (background
checks, security training, security practices, etc.) are all important -
the most important element is to focus on the people. If you don't trust
them, don't hire them.  And then keep them happy once you hire them.

Btw, this doesn't rule out all the simple stuff of ensuring you're
leveraging 2FA for all tools, data security do's and don'ts discussion,
etc. etc.


